[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Bbf Biochar Cic (CCS08)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Biochar is the charcoal-like solid product of heating biomass in very low-oxygen 
[normal]conditions. Biochar usually contains a lot of carbon which is tightly fixed in molecules that are resistant to microbial breakdown, meaning that the carbon persists in soil for hundreds to thousands of years  - long enough to be a useful way of reducing th
[normal]e CO
[normal]2
[normal] concentration in the atmosphere. Biochar is also a soil improver – it adds nutrients, modulates the pH, helps to store moisture in dry soils, increases the microbial activity, changes the soil structure, and so on. Biochar can make a major contribution to
[normal] the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s decarbonisation ambitions – especially in relation to the land-use, agricultural and bioenergy sectors – while enhancing the long-term health of soils. 
[normal]The 
[normal]potential
[normal] role of biochar in reducing carbon is between 
[normal]3.5 to 22 million tonnes CO[bold]2[bold] abate[bold]ment per year[bold] 
[normal](benefitting
[normal] 
[normal]between 4 and 28%
[normal] of 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s
[normal] agricultural land
[normal] over a 20 year period
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]However, biochar is a relatively new idea and much work remains to be done on making the underpinning technologies reliable and economically viable and on de
[normal]monstrating the value of biochar in agricultural and other settings.  The UK Government can assist by establishing a carb
[normal]on offsetting value for biochar 
[normal]allowing trading into the EU ETS  (as is already allowed for CO
[normal]2
[normal] capture and geological storage) and/or
[normal] allowing biochar to contribute to meeting company or organizational carbon
[normal] emission reduction
[normal] targets.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The British Biochar
[normal] Foundation (BBF) CIC
[normal]. was founded in 2013 to represent the wide range of individuals, groups, companies and other organisations in the UK which have an interest in biochar. The BBF has 197 individual members (as of August 2013) and the members come from research and developme
[normal]nt, private sector, consultancy, public sector, nature and conservation bodies, community groups and charities. In June 2013, 110 BBF members participated in the BBF’s inaugural event in Oxford.  In August 2013, a new Board has been established and will me
[normal]et for the first time in September. The aim of the BBF is to represent the emerging biochar sector in the UK in all its diversity. Our submission reflects the opinions of the BBF Board.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Biochar is a solid 
[normal]charcoal
[normal]-like
[normal] 
[normal]material, 
[normal]obtained from thermochemical conversion of biomass in an oxygen-limited environment that is used for the long-term storage of carbon in the environment and for soil improvement. Because the carbon in 
[normal]biochar is derived from CO
[normal]2
[normal] through photosynthesis, there is the potential for biochar to be a carbon-negative energy generation 
[normal]technology
[normal], through beneficial use of the energy produced during its manufacture.
[normal] A study undertaken for DEFRA and DECC in 2009
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]Shackley and Sohi, 2010
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal]concluded that biochar could contribute between
[normal] 3.5
[normal] million tonnes
[normal] (Mt)
[normal] C
[normal]O
[normal]2
[normal] (equivalent) abatement per year to 
[normal]22
[normal] 
[normal]Mt
[normal]C
[normal]O
[normal]2
[normal]eq
[normal] abatement per year 
[normal]depending on 
[normal]scenario, this representing 0.3 – 3% of 1990 UK greenhouse gas emissions or
[normal] 1.5 – 10% of the emission r
[normal]eductions required by 2020 (
[normal]Table 1).
[normal] (In this note, we will convert all carbon and non-CO
[normal]2
[normal] greenhouse gases into units of CO
[normal]2
[normal] equivalence or CO
[normal]2
[normal]eq using conventional conversion factors). 
[normal]The wide range is explained by uncertain
[normal]ty regarding the quantity of available biomass feedstocks, with the very high scenario implying that a reasonable percentage of suitable, sustainable biomass feedstocks are directed towards biochar production. 
[normal]Carbon abatement from agriculture and forestr
[normal]y as whole f
[normal]or the UK is c. 50 M
[normal]tCO2eq. A study for the Committee on Climate Change calculated emissions reductions from UK agriculture and soils of between 1.5 and 10  MtCO
[normal]2
[normal]eq per year (assuming a maximum abatement cost of ≤£100/tCO
[normal]2
[normal]eq) (MacLeod et al., 2
[normal]010). The potentially large 
[normal]role of biochar
[normal] in reducing greenhouse gas emissions from 
[normal]agriculture 
[normal]comes from using
[normal] a large amount of organic waste
[normal] (
[normal]much of which is not currently used effectively for other purposes)
[normal] and avoiding its decomposition to methan
[normal]e
[normal]. 
